WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:24.260
Between 1590 and 1595 Mughal artists Mohesh and Kesav created this painting, Emperor Akbar hunting wild asses.

2
00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:40.880
He is instructed by higher powers to “protect his holy person and be more careful in guarding it.”

3
00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:51.490
The moment in which Akbar collapses portrays inner-retrospect and enlightenment.

4
00:01:14.950 --> 00:01:20.950
The buildings in the background are the beautiful village of Harhari.

5
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:48.283
As illustrated in the Akbarnama the central figure, Akbar, travels on foot with a group of scouts until they come across a large herd of asses.

6
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:39.766
They see the wild game laying dead on the ground and Akbar motionless under a tree.

7
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:47.583
Akbar is depicted in this painting in a moment of weakness and exhaustion.

8
00:02:51.667 --> 00:02:58.555
The scouts frantically try to think of ways to bring the Emperor water.

9
00:02:58.555 --> 00:03:06.450
They decide to send some water carriers back through the desert to retrieve water in Harhari.

10
00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:13.650
In the distance of this painting the water carriers are seen

11
00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:27.200
The Mughal Emperor Akbar encouraged narrative art forms in the Mughal Period.